review: I finished this book a few days ago and since I have been puzzling over whether I hate it or not, what I should make of it.I started The Age of InnoceI finished this book a few days ago and since I have been puzzling over whether I hate it or not, what I should make of it.I started The Age of Innocence with very high expectations after having been deeply impressed by The House of Mirth, a story which I loved and was completely hooked from its first page, even after I finished it, I kept thinking about it for even a longer time and finally, I decided to shelve it among my favorites. I decided to find some other works of hers, and on picking this - I expected such same experience from her best-known work, but I was disappointed, several times I wanted to abandon it but kept reading I had to finish it, always expecting something might happen, an action, a surprise. But nothing!On one hand, the characters are very well built and believable, the novel makes a good portrait and criticism of the New York society of the last quarter of the 19th century. Also, it has refined and beautiful writing, lofty (but not pathetic) language, and is also very sensitive.Apart from that, I thought there was something off about the whole book and I couldn’t point out what exactly. I found the conclusion very disappointing, although I honestly don’t know what kind of an ending would make me think again about this book. Two stars for the writing...more

review: I loved this book. I think it's a huge achievement from Philip Roth. I'm looking forward to read every other book he's written.Here is my favourite paI loved this book. I think it's a huge achievement from Philip Roth. I'm looking forward to read every other book he's written.Here is my favourite passage;"You fight your superficiality, your shallowness, so as to try to come at people without unreal expectations, without an overload of bias or hope or arrogance, as untanklike as you can be, sans cannon and machine guns and steel plating half a foot thick: you come at them unmenscingly on your own ten toes instead of tearing up the turf with your caterpillar treads, take them on with an open mind, as equals, man to man, as we used to say, and yet you never fail to get them wrong. You might as well have the "brain of a tank. You get them wrong before you meet them, while you're anticipating meeting them; you get them wrong while you're with them; and then you go home to tell somebody else about the meeting and you get them all wrong again. Since the same generally goes for them with you, the whole thing is really a dazzling illusion empty of all perception, an astonishing farce of misperception. And yet what are we to do about this terribly significant business of "other people, which gets bled of the significance we think it has and takes on instead a significance that is ludicrous, so ill-equipped are we all to envision one another's interior workings and invisible aims? Is everyone to go off and lock the door and sit secluded like the lonely writers do, in a soundproof cell, summoning people out of words and then proposing that these word people are closer to the real thing than the real people that we mangle with our ignorance every day? The fact remains that getting people right is not what living is all about anyway, it's getting them wrong that is living, getting them wrong and wrong and wrong and then, on careful reconsideration, getting them wrong again. That's how we know we're alive we're wrong. Maybe the best thing would be to forget being right or wrong about people and just go along for the ride. But if you can do that-well, lucky you."...more

review: In this slim volume, Ayn Rand de-mysticizes writing and maintains that writing is a rational sphere governed by rationally identifiable principles. ShIn this slim volume, Ayn Rand de-mysticizes writing and maintains that writing is a rational sphere governed by rationally identifiable principles. She says, "What you need for nonfiction writing is what you need for life in general: an orderly method of thinking.”She goes on to provide a clear guide to the process of writing from choosing a subject and theme to creating an outline, first draft, and editing. One of the most interesting parts was her psychological analysis on the different roles played by the conscious mind and the subconscious in the process of writing i.e writing under the direction of the subconscious and then later consciously edit it. Also, how thinking objectively can help in problem-solving and performing complex tasks i.e by considering the epistemology and psycho-epistemology aspects of the mind.A short and quite insightful book that will help one become a better thinker and hence a better writer....more

review: All the bits and pieces coated uniformly, like a salad of despair This is my first reading of Thomas Pynchon and fortunately my favorite post-modernisAll the bits and pieces coated uniformly, like a salad of despair This is my first reading of Thomas Pynchon and fortunately my favorite post-modernism work. The book is tiny less than 200 pages but it has taken me almost two weeks to finish it.The character of Oedipa Maas will stay with me for a long time, I thought she’s by far the most interesting female character I read in a long time. Always finding patterns and assigning meanings through series of coincidences. The other characters names are nothing short ludicrous I mean how on earth does someone names a male figure Mucho Maas, Dr Hilarious, Pierce Inverarity, a rock band The Paranoids? Just to mention some.Pychon uses a sort of magical lucidity akin to a psychedelic trip to paint Oedipa's journey in such a confusing story filled with unusual coincidences, places, symbols, relationship in so many layers which are subject to many interpretations. But his descriptions feel alive, it is as if he's not really speaking about things of this world but rather some sort of mirror image with dark, sort of magical ominous undertones to it. I didn't even know how to distinguish important details but I surely had a great time with it.Do you want answers? A clearly defined plot with direction and clarity? A satisfying conclusion? If yes, then you won't like this book. This book is cryptic and mysterious. There are no real answers to be found here. There's no moral, no lesson, no real reason to anything in this book, just a search for truth that gets more slippery as the pages tum.I will need to read this one again and some other work form Pynchon as well....more

review: The common reader... differs from the critic and the scholar. He is worse educated, and nature has not gifted him so generously. He reads for his own The common reader... differs from the critic and the scholar. He is worse educated, and nature has not gifted him so generously. He reads for his own pleasure rather than to impart knowledge or correct the opinions of others. Above all, he is guided by an instinct to create for himself, out of whatever odds and ends he can come by, some kind of whole — a portrait of a man, a sketch of an age, a theory of the art of writing.Virginia Woolf. The Common Reader: First SeriesI too am a common reader and I felt in great company with her when reading this. Her hunger for books is not much unfamiliar to mine, and as far as reading is concerned this felt like a conversation with myself about my relationship with the books I own, have read, have abandoned, inherited, borrowed or forgotten.The Common Reader is a slim collection of 18 essays about her lifelong affair with books. While some essays went over my head, her take on writers and subjects I'm familiar with was really thrilling. I enjoyed her pieces on Montaigne, Austen and the Brontë's in particular, also her writing on literary criticism and contemporary art really interested and it felt just as relevant and insightful now as it must have been at the time. She is as sharp and illuminating as always. ...more

title: The Sea, the Sea
author: Murdoch, Iris
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: What writing talent!It is always better to give a book a chance, when you begin a book expecting one thing, but you get something completely differentWhat writing talent!It is always better to give a book a chance, when you begin a book expecting one thing, but you get something completely different, it may turn out that the book you have been avoiding becomes your favorite! As it happened to me this time.Initially, I thought that this book would be about the sea, a lonely life on the shore, a leisurely narration and diary entries about the everyday life of a former theater director, who decided to retire and escape from his former life in the theatre. At first it really was so, but then the book took a queer turn and strange things started happening in the house as more and more people come to visit.True, I did not expect and was amazed at the impression the main character made on me, his memoir narration, the discourse on the life he had lived and especially his obsession with the love of his life. With extraordinary psychological insights Murdoch describes all the agonizing and tormenting ideas that keep a tight and uncontrollable grip of the narrator's mind, driving him deeper and deeper into a state of wild jealousy.The book is confusing as it is great, it reads like a surreal dream sometimes but yet realistic in its descriptions. It is strange, moving and enigmatic. It is memorable, above all, because of its strange atmosphere - a past that is inevitable, the nightmare that is everyday life....more

title: Shuggie Bain
author: Stuart, Douglas*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: As he cracked his way across the frozen burns he consoled himself, knowing exactly what her day looked like. There was comfort in the fact that wh As he cracked his way across the frozen burns he consoled himself, knowing exactly what her day looked like. There was comfort in the fact that whether sober or not, it largely followed the same trapped routine! Shuggie Bain takes place in 1980's Glasgow under the constraints of Thatcherism. A city that has been absolutely decimated by loss of industries - as a working-class city, "Glasgow was losing its purpose." Laid out as snippets cast over 1981 to 1992, the story focuses on Agnes Bain and her family - her husband, Shug; her daughter, Catherine; and her sons, Leek and Shuggie. In 448 pages, we largely follow Agnes and her youngest son Shuggie living beneath the strain of poverty. Shuggie Bain is not an easy read, often uncomfortable and filled with heartbreaking depiction of alcoholism, of poverty, of loss of agency, of coming of age, of abuse. Despite all of these heavy themes, the strongest theme of all is love. Love despite someone choosing alcohol over you, love in the very smallest moments of hope and love in a lasting friendship that begins with acceptance.Probably the best novel of 2020...more

review: This is one of the strangest book I've ever read! Dark in its irony and deeply allegorical, the writer manages to play with realities using bone-dry lThis is one of the strangest book I've ever read! Dark in its irony and deeply allegorical, the writer manages to play with realities using bone-dry language, death, disability, bicycles etc, creating surreal situations and places, so original and surprisingly blended with reality that one can not help but envy the brain from which these things emanate. Extensive footnotes stretching across several pages referencing to de Selby was the best part of the book for me; de Selby (imaginary author of several works of speculative philosophy and natural history (almost all of which were ludicrous), and an expert on almost everything), is mentioned and discussed in long footnotes while having apparent little relationship to the main narration. (except for the narrator’s interest in his writings). The footnotes are usually filled with disagreements among his five or six critics and commentators.Excellent book but far too hallucinatory for my taste....more

review: A widely influential work, The Conquest of Bread is one of those books which might be more relevant today than it was when it was first written. KropoA widely influential work, The Conquest of Bread is one of those books which might be more relevant today than it was when it was first written. Kropotkin identifies a series of problems and devices possible solutions like his empasis on technological innovation freer of humankind, how technology will allow for more leisure time and to produce everything for all people, from food to luxury, if only we break down the artificial social structures holding us back. A truly revolutionary work that point to a possible future that is certainly better than our present, beyond differences of education, gender, race or nation, a firm belief in the innate goodness of humans and an organization of society which is above all fair. What he predicts and claims here is the idea that no one needs to go hungry or shelterless, but they do because of an unfair distribution of food and housing.Essential read....more

review: Dubliners is, honestly, one of the best shortstory books I've read so far. It has a very sober, clean, simple prose; that gives it even more strength Dubliners is, honestly, one of the best shortstory books I've read so far. It has a very sober, clean, simple prose; that gives it even more strength and solidity.The stories complement and enrich each other. At the end of it you have the knowledge of the Dublin society, its inhabitants like a journey from childhood to death. Their traditions, customs, hobbies, psychology and everything in between.Joyce is a genius, a god, a creator of worlds, a maker of lives; You read and read and it's like being in Dublin with him, going from bar to bar, from street to street. He made me feel like a Dubliner with his magical and realistic changes of time, space and plane of reality. And that after reading the Ulysses I thought that I could not marvel more, how wrong I was...more

review: A phenomenal and masterful exploration of grief and queer love.I think this is, in many ways an incredible book. The writing is stunning, and there isA phenomenal and masterful exploration of grief and queer love.I think this is, in many ways an incredible book. The writing is stunning, and there is so much about the nasty little things that make us human. George's homosexuality is something that defines this book and the character himself but the fact that there isn't any eroticism associated within the pages was very refreshing to me. His love and grief with the loss of Jim is very human and homosexuality is merely a descriptor within the context.There are some few things about this novel that I found somehow uncomfortable - the sexism towards women, the obsession with youth and race etc but I'm able to put those gripes aside due to the historical context -1964. This book was sad, funny, and portrayed the truth of human emotions in such a realistic way that I am definitely going to check out more of Isherwood's work....more

review: "Dear friend now in the dusty clockless hours of the town when the streets lie black and steaming in the wake of the watertrucks and now when the drun"Dear friend now in the dusty clockless hours of the town when the streets lie black and steaming in the wake of the watertrucks and now when the drunk and the homeless have washed up in the lee of walls in alleys or abandoned lots and cats go forth highshouldered and lean in the grim perimeters about, now in these sootblacked brick or cobbled corridors where lightwire shadows make a gothic harp of cellar doors no soul shall walk save you...."As in many of his books, the world depicted in Cormac McCarthy's books is gloomy, often a hopeless place filled with odd characters facing various problems. It's no different with Suttree.The novel doesn't have a plot. Written with immeasurable details, dense prose that forces you to slow down, process and appreciate this piece of work. How dripping with life it actually is. A lot of nothing happens. We follow our protagonist Suttree who seems to be in search for authentic experiences, we witness random episodes from Suttree's life and the encounters he has with many memorable but odd characters. Thematically it's hard to pin down what Suttree is about, it's might be death or probably redemption or absolute nothing but meandering through life's eternal winter huddling around small canfires with other lost souls. Suttree is a grotesque story of loneliness, suffering and the inability to find peace...more

review: Doctor Zhivago is a work that tells us about a doctor's adventures throughout his life, going through two World Wars and two Revolutions. In the novelDoctor Zhivago is a work that tells us about a doctor's adventures throughout his life, going through two World Wars and two Revolutions. In the novel Pasternack brings us up to date with the factors that triggered the Russian Revolution of 1917, the scenario where the events took place, as well as the psychological drama that affected the people at the time, their disillusions to the tsarist political system, the hopes deposited in a new government system (socialism), as well as the intense fighting between the White Army (Mensheviks) and the Red Army (Bosheviks) after the overthrow of the tsarist imperialist system.Zhivago is a doctor who serves as a volunteer in the First World War, where he meets Lara and there he meets another side of his capacity for love, a passion that overwhelms him anxiously. Here the author puts the main character in a position to reconsider his idealism, making him reach a balanced maturity. In the story the author is displays a web of characters that fate will make them meet again and againWhile the main story unfolds the reader sees the atrocities of communism, absurdity of war and the dent that all this left in to the Russian people. A reading, which despite its 700 pages has been light, emotional and exciting....more

review: “Good heavens! why did I marry?” - Emma BovaryMadame Bovary is a true novel of life, a writing reflected by a sad soul drowning in illusions. A bit   “Good heavens! why did I marry?” - Emma BovaryMadame Bovary is a true novel of life, a writing reflected by a sad soul drowning in illusions. A bit slow in the beginning but all its charm is revealed when every word or sentence penetrates the soul of the reader and leaves a notch there.A classic, multilayered novel that engross the reader with the lessons it offers (a critique of dangerous and uneducated bourgeoisie, a critique of the clergy who can not understand Emma's real pain etc etc.) and the realistic way in which events are presented; bad things happen and then life goes on.Emma is portrayed as a tragic figure who can not escape from her social class and consequently from her own fate that stands painlessly in-front of her, while Charles who is presented as a kind of idiot early in the book, is a plain kind of a man with very plain tastes. Hes satisfied the life he carves out for himself and thinks that his wife is just as happy as he is.A man, on the contrary, should he not know everything, excel in manifold activities, initiate you into the energies of passion, the refinements of life, all mysteries? But this one taught nothing, knew nothing, wished nothing. He thought her happy; and she resented this easy calm, this serene heaviness, the very happiness she gave him.   At bottom of her heart, however, she was waiting for something to happen. Like shipwrecked sailors, she turned despairing eyes upon the solitude of her life, seeking afar off some white sail in the mists of the horizon. She did not know what this chance would be, what wind would bring it her, towards what shore it would drive her, if it would be a shallop or a three-decker, laden with anguish or full of bliss to the portholes. But each morning, as she awoke, she hoped it would come that day; she listened to every sound, sprang up with a start, wondered that it did not come; then at sunset, always more saddened, she longed for the morrow. 5-Stars, definitely one of my favorites....more

review: O McCarthy!This is the third McCarthy's book I read this year. And I think I will let him rest for now. Not because it is bad but on the contrary, theO McCarthy!This is the third McCarthy's book I read this year. And I think I will let him rest for now. Not because it is bad but on the contrary, the bastard is too good that if I sink a little more into his books they end up making me sad and disgusted; he makes me hate the world. When I finished reading The Road all I wanted was to cry, when I finished reading No Country for Old Men all I wanted was to be accompanied. When I picked up Blood Meridian, I realized, after few pages that this book will require a very special effort reading it and several times I thought of abandoning it and when I finished it, well it's hard to know what he wanted, but what I did want was to stop reading McCarthy a bit.The bastard took such a remarkable job of describing the wild west, reflecting Evil, violence, war by/on man that I think he got a little out of hand. The book is slow, but on purpose, everything is completely premeditated. I don't want to tell you what you will read if you decide to venture into this book, what I will say is that you will learn the meaning of excessive violence.The McCarthy characters are without a doubt unforgettable and The Judge I think is the most unforgettable of all. review: Celine's writing bored me to death, I have never came across anything like it before. It almost seems to be like sitting at the table with a drunk andCeline's writing bored me to death, I have never came across anything like it before. It almost seems to be like sitting at the table with a drunk and hearing him talk about his life for a whole night, on one hand you are interested in the other you wouldn't want to listen to him because he unmasks all that is more atrocious, petty and rot in him.It is a fascinating, intoxicating book of sublime melancholic clarity. It decisively and directly describes a supposedly autobiography - (twenty years of the life) of a person who has nothing good to offer; a misanthrope, a coward, a misogyny, violent and an egoist. Surrounded by characters who have nothing better to offer, difficult to classify, everything is unexpected and diffuse.However, we recognize a thousand details and hundreds of reflections that ring true even if they are excessively pessimistic. Reflections on anarchy, on heroism, on nationalism, on capitalism; the reverse side of everything that makes up our society is brought to light. It also, in large part of the book, portrays the existential bewilderment and vital anguish in time of war, in absolute crisis, with overwhelming sensitivity. The grim reality, that which inevitably resembles to the darkest night, the one we intend to avoid despite being hidden but omnipresent: The loneliness of man and the meanness and misery of his spirit.The end of the book allows us to hope that our journey does not end at night....more

review: The religious stage requires passionate, subjective belief rather than objective proof, in the paradoxical and the absurd.So, what’s the absurd? That The religious stage requires passionate, subjective belief rather than objective proof, in the paradoxical and the absurd.So, what’s the absurd? That which Christianity asks us to accept as true, that God became man born of a virgin, suffered, died and was resurrected.According to Kierkegaard Abraham was the ultimate “knight of faith”. Without doubt there is no faith, and so in a state of “fear and trembling” Abraham was willing to break the universal moral law against murder by agreeing to kill his own son, Isaac.I don't believe in God, I'm one of those people Kierkegaard wrote about who discards religion because of science and I cant get passed reason, but disagreeing with a writer is not the basis for my enjoying his/her writing. And i would like to comment just a bit on this little work.Kierkegaard writes;"...passion is necessary. Every movement comes about by passion. And no reflection can bring a movement about."  1. Is irrationality necessarily illogical or does it have its own logic; is the law of non-contradiction inherent in human nature? In a sense (as Kierkegaard writes of Abraham and Isaac) where the sacrifice of his son is both murder contrary to morality and faith according to divine will, hence the significance of anxiety/anguish/angst amongst the existential philosophers. Abrahams intent is irrational; and that it is both murder and sacrifice according the human mind and hence is irrational in different fields of Philosophy i.e Ethics resulting to contradiction.  2. Must all areas of philosophy cohere or must we take the either/or position of logic-either Ethics or Metaphysics, yet not both? I found Kierkegaard's writing really accessible. This is my first Kierkegaard and Im sure it won't be the last...more

What book about genocide can be called interesting book. This book is a comprehensive account (in great writing and superb journalistic skills) of what happened in Rwanda while the rest of the world sat back and did nothing during the 1994 genocide.The book is a series of journalistic accounts of the Rwandan Genocide. In many ways, it is horrific, but of incredible importance. Highly recommend this book for anyone interested in history and want better idea about what really happened in the genocide. Unlike any movie I have watched about the massacre, the author gets the reader to see or imagine the true insanity of the Hutu's systematic slaughter of the Tutsis.
